description: From Middle French précéder, from Latin praecēdō, from prae- + cēdō.

entries.meaning: Brief editorial preface (usually to an article or essay)

verbs.description: precede (third-person singular simple present precedes, present participle preceding, simple past and past participle preceded)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To go before, go in front of.
(transitive) To cause to be preceded; to preface; to introduce.
examples: It has been usual to precede hostilities by a public declaration communicated to the enemy.

entries.meaning: (transitive) To have higher rank than (someone or something else).
